<dl id="n03124a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03124a">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03124a"> 124(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Biggest possible <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03124a"><li>FW 412.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/lexpA.htm#n03124a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/l39pA.htm#n03124a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03124a">MS BL 47482b-11</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:023 <a name="pA1d" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pA1d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/p/pa1d.htm#n03124a">Draft: III&sect;1A.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In Chaucer&apos;s <cite>Troilus and Criseyde</cite>, one of the greatest love-poems ever written and probably a greater work of art than any of the <cite>Canterbury Tales</cite>, there is a true symbolic interpretation of an anxiety dream. Troilus was pining for his love, Criseyde, who had been led back by Diomede to the Greeks in exchange for Antenor. Troilus dreamt that he saw a boar asleep in the sun and that Criseyde was embracing and kissing it. <small> Albert Mordell, <a name="AMEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMEM"><cite title="source">The Erotic Motive in Literature</cite></a> (1919) p.160</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
